00:06:05.420 --> 00:06:08.676
What makes California's system unique?

00:06:08.676 --> 00:06:12.509
California's system is
unique because it began

00:06:13.615 --> 00:06:15.038
with families.

00:06:15.038 --> 00:06:17.635
It began with families
saying, "I want an alternative

00:06:17.635 --> 00:06:20.928
"that's different from
institutional care."

00:06:20.928 --> 00:06:24.624
In the 1960s, California
supported over 13,000 individuals

00:06:24.624 --> 00:06:27.386
with developmental
disabilities in state-run

00:06:27.386 --> 00:06:30.161
developmental centers and
there was a waiting list

00:06:30.161 --> 00:06:31.463
to get in.

00:06:31.463 --> 00:06:33.727
Families came to the legislature and said,

00:06:33.727 --> 00:06:36.310
"there has to be a better way."

00:06:37.602 --> 00:06:41.769
Through cooperation between
both republicans and democrats,

00:06:42.794 --> 00:06:45.346
the service system was developed.

00:06:45.346 --> 00:06:48.544
To this day, it remains widely supported

00:06:48.544 --> 00:06:50.294
in a bi-partisan way.

00:06:51.911 --> 00:06:54.488
At that time, federal
funding was only available

00:06:54.488 --> 00:06:57.612
for institutional care, but
California made a commitment

00:06:57.612 --> 00:07:00.378
to serve people with
developmental disabilities

00:07:00.378 --> 00:07:04.463
in community settings, even without that.

00:07:04.463 --> 00:07:05.773
Now every state in the country has

00:07:05.773 --> 00:07:09.907
a developmental services
system that is community based,

00:07:09.907 --> 00:07:14.246
but ours remains one of
the few entitlement states.

00:07:14.246 --> 00:07:16.082
Other states will tell you
they're an entitlement.

00:07:16.082 --> 00:07:18.582
We like to disagree with them.

00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:23.167
And the other thing that
makes our system really unique

00:07:23.167 --> 00:07:25.670
is it's not government run.

00:07:25.670 --> 00:07:29.173
It is designed to be responsive
to the individual needs

00:07:29.173 --> 00:07:32.840
of individual communities
because the state,

00:07:34.104 --> 00:07:35.562
when they were putting
the system together,

00:07:35.562 --> 00:07:38.730
came to the realization that
the needs of individuals

00:07:38.730 --> 00:07:42.501
and families in this
area are very different

00:07:42.501 --> 00:07:46.327
than those of individuals
and families in Fresno.

00:07:46.327 --> 00:07:48.748
The challenges and the gaps in services

00:07:48.748 --> 00:07:50.392
are all very different.

00:07:50.392 --> 00:07:55.067
Each regional center has an
independent board of directors

00:07:55.067 --> 00:07:58.860
and 50% of that board
must be either individuals

00:07:58.860 --> 00:08:01.088
with developmental disabilities
or their family members

00:08:01.088 --> 00:08:03.586
to ensure that the
system remains responsive

00:08:03.586 --> 00:08:05.586
to those who rely on it.

00:08:07.886 --> 00:08:09.218
Really, the regional center is here

00:08:09.218 --> 00:08:11.718
for three real basic purposes.

00:08:12.657 --> 00:08:14.693
To help infants and toddlers to reach

00:08:14.693 --> 00:08:16.694
their developmental potential.

00:08:16.694 --> 00:08:19.574
To help children to stay at
home with their families,

00:08:19.574 --> 00:08:20.940
because remember, this was at a time

00:08:20.940 --> 00:08:24.310
when if you had a child with
a developmental disability,

00:08:24.310 --> 00:08:26.542
you could either put
them on that waiting list

00:08:26.542 --> 00:08:28.833
for the developmental center,
or you could take them home

00:08:28.833 --> 00:08:31.349
and take care of them
entirely on your own,

00:08:31.349 --> 00:08:33.556
and too many families were
making the first choice

00:08:33.556 --> 00:08:35.439
out of necessity.

00:08:35.439 --> 00:08:38.006
And then the third goal of the
system is to support adults

00:08:38.006 --> 00:08:41.089
to live as independently as possible.

00:08:43.648 --> 00:08:46.648
Regional centers don't do
the day-to-day hands-on work

00:08:46.648 --> 00:08:49.147
with individuals, but they fulfill a lot

00:08:49.147 --> 00:08:50.904
of important functions.

00:08:50.904 --> 00:08:53.538
They provide intake and
eligibility to ensure

00:08:53.538 --> 00:08:57.153
that people who qualify for
services are brought in.

00:08:57.153 --> 00:09:00.059
They provide lifelong service planning.

00:09:00.059 --> 00:09:02.693
Talking about what is it that
you need and how can we help

00:09:02.693 --> 00:09:03.888
you get it?

00:09:03.888 --> 00:09:08.255
They provide clinical support,
oftentimes acting as a hub

00:09:08.255 --> 00:09:12.861
of excellence for medical
information in their communities.

00:09:12.861 --> 00:09:15.538
Regional centers were designed
to fill in gaps in services.

00:09:15.538 --> 00:09:19.077
They aren't here to take
the place of other services,

00:09:19.077 --> 00:09:22.662
but they're here to help
you access other services

00:09:22.662 --> 00:09:24.857
in your community through
things such as MediCal,

00:09:24.857 --> 00:09:27.399
in-home supportive
services, special education,

00:09:27.399 --> 00:09:28.854
and the like.

00:09:28.854 --> 00:09:31.560
And lastly, regional centers
fulfill a critical function

00:09:31.560 --> 00:09:34.928
in meeting federal expectations
because while the system

00:09:34.928 --> 00:09:38.230
was started without
federal dollars, today,

00:09:38.230 --> 00:09:42.561
it relies on a tremendous
amount of federal funding.

00:09:42.561 --> 00:09:46.305
Speaking of which, you'll
see that, I wish the colors

00:09:46.305 --> 00:09:48.906
came out a little better, but that's okay.

00:09:48.906 --> 00:09:52.077
The first 40% of the funding in our system

00:09:52.077 --> 00:09:54.984
is federal dollars and so
it's essential that we meet

00:09:54.984 --> 00:09:57.602
those expectations of
the federal government

00:09:57.602 --> 00:09:59.618
and keep those dollars coming.

00:09:59.618 --> 00:10:02.928
At this time, the Regional
Center System has a total budget

00:10:02.928 --> 00:10:07.095
of 6.1 billion dollars or so,
with about 2.5 billion of that

00:10:08.912 --> 00:10:11.745
coming from federal reimbursement.

00:10:14.782 --> 00:10:15.975
Because the money, we care a lot

00:10:15.975 --> 00:10:19.975
about what the federal
government thinks, right?

00:10:21.478 --> 00:10:23.461
The way our service system is structured,

00:10:23.461 --> 00:10:26.635
and please excuse the crude flowchart.

00:10:26.635 --> 00:10:28.557
It was my first time making
one and I was super proud

00:10:28.557 --> 00:10:30.372
of it, so I stuck it on the slide.

00:10:30.372 --> 00:10:33.270
(audience laughs)

00:10:33.270 --> 00:10:36.617
But basically, service providers report

00:10:36.617 --> 00:10:39.962
to the regional center about the progress

00:10:39.962 --> 00:10:44.871
of the individual, as well
as for billing purposes.

00:10:44.871 --> 00:10:46.582
The regional centers bill

00:10:46.582 --> 00:10:48.471
the Department of Developmental Services.

00:10:48.471 --> 00:10:50.254
The Department of
Developmental Services bills

00:10:50.254 --> 00:10:53.437
the federal government, money comes out

00:10:53.437 --> 00:10:55.267
of the federal government,
and it all goes back up

00:10:55.267 --> 00:10:57.467
the stream the other direction.

00:10:57.467 --> 00:11:01.257
The reason that it all goes
through, or the vast majority

00:11:01.257 --> 00:11:03.578
of it goes through the
Department of Health Care Service

00:11:03.578 --> 00:11:06.828
is they are what we call in California,

00:11:08.787 --> 00:11:11.607
what we call our single
state entity for Medicaid.

00:11:11.607 --> 00:11:13.366
Basically the federal
government doesn't wanna talk

00:11:13.366 --> 00:11:15.949
to every department in
this state or in any state,

00:11:15.949 --> 00:11:19.655
for that matter, so most of
this funding is Medicaid funding

00:11:19.655 --> 00:11:20.908
and it has to flow through

00:11:20.908 --> 00:11:24.158
the Department of Health Care Services.

00:11:28.622 --> 00:11:31.864
The federal government
pushes a lot of initiatives

00:11:31.864 --> 00:11:36.169
on states, and the good
news is that in California,

00:11:36.169 --> 00:11:38.353
we've always had a very
progressive system.

00:11:38.353 --> 00:11:40.672
We've always wanted to
see people participating

00:11:40.672 --> 00:11:41.883
in their communities.

00:11:41.883 --> 00:11:46.050
We've always wanted to see
people living independent lives

00:11:47.572 --> 00:11:50.752
and so some of the trends
that are being pushed

00:11:50.752 --> 00:11:53.059
at the federal government,
at the federal level,

00:11:53.059 --> 00:11:55.654
are much tougher for
other states than they are

00:11:55.654 --> 00:11:58.282
for California at this time.

00:11:58.282 --> 00:12:00.528
Some pose a challenge,
frankly, because of the scale

00:12:00.528 --> 00:12:01.694
of our system.

00:12:01.694 --> 00:12:05.161
We serve 300,000 individuals
with developmental disabilities

00:12:05.161 --> 00:12:07.037
in the state of California.

00:12:07.037 --> 00:12:11.131
Other states, for example,
the state of Tennessee,

00:12:11.131 --> 00:12:12.714
serves about 8,000.

00:12:14.694 --> 00:12:17.703
You'll begin to see why
that's a challenge for us.

00:12:17.703 --> 00:12:19.994
First and foremost, the federal government

00:12:19.994 --> 00:12:22.269
wants to see person-centered planning.

00:12:22.269 --> 00:12:24.484
They want to see that the
person and their needs

00:12:24.484 --> 00:12:27.912
and their individual wants
and desires are central

00:12:27.912 --> 00:12:31.480
to the determination of what
services they will receive.

00:12:31.480 --> 00:12:33.598
I heard one speaker one time refer to this

00:12:33.598 --> 00:12:37.917
as finding that balance
between what someone needs

00:12:37.917 --> 00:12:39.877
and what someone wants.

00:12:39.877 --> 00:12:44.757
What the person requires
and what makes their life

00:12:44.757 --> 00:12:46.180
worth living.

00:12:46.180 --> 00:12:48.391
And that's really how we look at it.

00:12:48.391 --> 00:12:52.673
It is possible to meet someone's
health and safety needs

00:12:52.673 --> 00:12:55.896
without really giving them
the life that they desire.

00:12:55.896 --> 00:12:58.492
And that's really the balance
that we strive to achieve

00:12:58.492 --> 00:13:00.534
here in California.

00:13:00.534 --> 00:13:04.052
We started doing person-centered
planning in one form

00:13:04.052 --> 00:13:08.181
in 1992 in this state and other
states are just now starting

00:13:08.181 --> 00:13:09.431
down this path.

00:13:10.756 --> 00:13:13.189
Conflict free case management.

00:13:13.189 --> 00:13:15.538
In California, as I
mentioned, regional centers

00:13:15.538 --> 00:13:18.373
don't provide that
day-to-day direct support.

00:13:18.373 --> 00:13:21.252
In some other states,
the agencies that provide

00:13:21.252 --> 00:13:24.033
the case management function
are also service providers

00:13:24.033 --> 00:13:27.477
and you could see the potential
for conflicts of interest

00:13:27.477 --> 00:13:28.310
there.

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:31.632
The federal government
wants to see higher levels

00:13:31.632 --> 00:13:33.316
of community integration.

00:13:33.316 --> 00:13:35.462
They wanna see people
out in their communities

00:13:35.462 --> 00:13:40.349
and they wanna see people
part of their communities.

00:13:40.349 --> 00:13:44.516
We are continuously growing
and changing in this way.

00:13:47.602 --> 00:13:51.024
Having less settings that
are set aside just for people

00:13:51.024 --> 00:13:54.324
with disabilities, and
finding more creative ways

00:13:54.324 --> 00:13:56.880
to support people in natural communities,

00:13:56.880 --> 00:13:58.685
which we believe is good,
not only for the individual,

00:13:58.685 --> 00:14:01.185
but for the community as well.

00:14:02.054 --> 00:14:03.924
There's also an emphasis on greater levels

00:14:03.924 --> 00:14:05.800
of community employment.

00:14:05.800 --> 00:14:10.028
As we know, employment
isn't just about a paycheck.

00:14:10.028 --> 00:14:13.482
It's about a sense of
belonging, it's about finding

00:14:13.482 --> 00:14:16.881
a community, it's about
creating a space for yourself

00:14:16.881 --> 00:14:20.667
in that community, and so the
emphasis at the federal level

00:14:20.667 --> 00:14:23.822
and at the state level as
well, is on helping people

00:14:23.822 --> 00:14:27.414
to find their place in this world.

00:14:27.414 --> 00:14:28.997
Measuring outcomes.

00:14:29.902 --> 00:14:33.652
We can really easily
measure what we provide,

00:14:35.379 --> 00:14:37.655
but we're working hard to begin to measure

00:14:37.655 --> 00:14:41.583
the ultimate impact on someone's life.

00:14:41.583 --> 00:14:43.925
We don't just wanna provide services.

00:14:43.925 --> 00:14:47.438
