The system is also asking
what services and supports

00:16:47.883 --> 00:16:49.985
will help the families to stay together.

00:16:49.985 --> 00:16:52.557
Here in California, 78% of individuals

00:16:52.557 --> 00:16:54.552
with developmental
disabilities live at home

00:16:54.552 --> 00:16:57.969
with their families and that is essential

00:17:00.021 --> 00:17:01.803
to the way our system works.

00:17:01.803 --> 00:17:03.716
Providing critical family support services

00:17:03.716 --> 00:17:06.270
to help families to stay together

00:17:06.270 --> 00:17:08.618
when that's the desired outcome.

00:17:08.618 --> 00:17:11.479
We're also beginning to look
at and continuing to look at,

00:17:11.479 --> 00:17:14.600
what are the opportunities
for what to do next?

00:17:14.600 --> 00:17:17.911
Where can we enhance the system?

00:17:17.911 --> 00:17:19.913
Finally, how can funding
be adjusted to ensure

00:17:19.913 --> 00:17:22.505
that it remains sustainable?

00:17:22.505 --> 00:17:25.589
We have an entitlement
system here in California.

00:17:25.589 --> 00:17:29.679
Individuals are entitled
to services and supports,

00:17:29.679 --> 00:17:33.596
but every year, the system must continue

00:17:33.596 --> 00:17:37.763
to seek out funding through
the legislative process.

00:17:39.843 --> 00:17:41.966
Concerns on the horizon.

00:17:41.966 --> 00:17:46.133
Now we're glancing across
the country to Washington.

00:17:46.969 --> 00:17:48.707
I know people in this
room are really concerned

00:17:48.707 --> 00:17:51.013
about all the things that
they're hearing out of Washington

00:17:51.013 --> 00:17:52.910
and so are we.

00:17:52.910 --> 00:17:56.159
The four things that
could have a major impact

00:17:56.159 --> 00:17:58.557
on our service system are,
of course, any changes

00:17:58.557 --> 00:18:00.781
to the Affordable Care Act.

00:18:00.781 --> 00:18:03.913
Some of our funding, as
I mentioned, much of it

00:18:03.913 --> 00:18:06.123
is Medicaid funding, so we serve

00:18:06.123 --> 00:18:08.596
the Medicaid expansion population.

00:18:08.596 --> 00:18:13.430
We also receive a few hundred
million dollars a year

00:18:13.430 --> 00:18:17.071
through an expansion of
federal funding specifically

00:18:17.071 --> 00:18:18.525
for our service system.

00:18:18.525 --> 00:18:20.225
That was part of the Affordable Care Act.

00:18:20.225 --> 00:18:22.539
We're continuing to watch these things.

00:18:22.539 --> 00:18:26.706
We also know that because
our system fills in gaps

00:18:29.205 --> 00:18:31.556
in services, that when new gaps open up,

00:18:31.556 --> 00:18:33.165
that poses a problem.

00:18:33.165 --> 00:18:35.858
If people begin to lose
health care or if they lose

00:18:35.858 --> 00:18:39.126
access to other services, that's a problem

00:18:39.126 --> 00:18:41.709
for the people that we support.

00:18:43.101 --> 00:18:47.202
We're also very concerned about
Medicaid funding structures.

00:18:47.202 --> 00:18:51.369
You hear, in Washington, talk
of Medicaid block granting

00:18:53.080 --> 00:18:56.332
and this, at least the
third time that idea's

00:18:56.332 --> 00:18:59.140
been put forward, but
we're still concerned

00:18:59.140 --> 00:19:01.140
for a number of reasons.

00:19:02.047 --> 00:19:04.036
First, Medicaid block
granting is really hard

00:19:04.036 --> 00:19:05.487
on high growth states.

00:19:05.487 --> 00:19:07.102
We're a high growth state.

00:19:07.102 --> 00:19:12.043
Additionally, we're unclear
what that will look like

00:19:12.043 --> 00:19:13.998
because Medicaid funds
don't just go to fund

00:19:13.998 --> 00:19:16.387
doctor's appointments
and physical therapy.

00:19:16.387 --> 00:19:18.669
They also go to fund a
number of social services

00:19:18.669 --> 00:19:22.060
through the Regional Center, through IHSS,

00:19:22.060 --> 00:19:23.787
through all kinds of things.

00:19:23.787 --> 00:19:27.287
That's a very real concern for the system.

00:19:30.396 --> 00:19:33.824
Any changes to Medicare, also
a concern for our system.

00:19:33.824 --> 00:19:36.775
We have a number of
people, particularly those

00:19:36.775 --> 00:19:39.208
who have the greatest
levels of medical fragility

00:19:39.208 --> 00:19:40.708
who are Medi-Medi.

00:19:41.626 --> 00:19:44.085
So changes to the
Medicare funding structure

00:19:44.085 --> 00:19:46.418
could adversely impact them.

00:19:48.148 --> 00:19:51.821
There's also talk of changes
to special education.

00:19:51.821 --> 00:19:55.404
Again, we look at the
comprehensive whole person

00:19:55.404 --> 00:19:59.334
and we have to think about
what are the challenges

00:19:59.334 --> 00:20:01.930
that not only our system will face,

00:20:01.930 --> 00:20:04.043
but that these individuals
that we support will face

00:20:04.043 --> 00:20:06.245
and their families will face.

00:20:06.245 --> 00:20:08.055
Those are things that
we continue to monitor

00:20:08.055 --> 00:20:12.222
and continue to try to
educate our lawmakers about.

00:20:19.720 --> 00:20:23.082
As if that's not
depressing enough (laughs),

00:20:23.082 --> 00:20:26.075
and sadly those are things
that keep me up at three AM

00:20:26.075 --> 00:20:28.345
thinking about Medicaid block granting.

00:20:28.345 --> 00:20:30.596
Hopefully you all, if
you're up at that hour

00:20:30.596 --> 00:20:33.665
have something else to worry about.

00:20:33.665 --> 00:20:35.143
A final thought.

00:20:35.143 --> 00:20:38.054
Our system turned 50 years old last year

00:20:38.054 --> 00:20:40.385
and there's a great video

00:20:40.385 --> 00:20:42.199
called We're Here To Speak For Justice.

00:20:42.199 --> 00:20:44.072
If you haven't seen it,
please take the time out

00:20:44.072 --> 00:20:44.906
to do it.

00:20:44.906 --> 00:20:47.828
It's from those inspirational
families who founded

00:20:47.828 --> 00:20:52.136
our system and who gave us the
backbone of what we do today.

00:20:52.136 --> 00:20:54.861
One of them said, "we were
clearing away new paths

00:20:54.861 --> 00:20:56.772
"to get the work done,
to get what we needed.

00:20:56.772 --> 00:20:59.550
"They didn't exist, so
we had to work on it

00:20:59.550 --> 00:21:01.506
"so that they did exist."

00:21:01.506 --> 00:21:04.057
Today, we consider ourselves
continuing to chart

00:21:04.057 --> 00:21:07.724
new paths where they
didn't exist yesterday.

00:21:10.648 --> 00:21:12.366
Any questions?

00:21:12.366 --> 00:21:15.366
(audience applause)

